               <msContents>
                  <summary>A panegyric account of the life and sayings of the Imam ‘Alī, by Muhammad Salih Husain Tirmiz̲ī with the <foreign>تخلص</foreign> Kashfī (d. A.H. 1061/ A.D. 1650 at Agra). The authoris a descendant of <name ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/33415216" key="person_33415216">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Niʻmat Allāh Valī, 1330?-1431</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">شاه نعمت الله ولى، سيد نور الدين</persName>
                     </name> and the son of the Sufi Mīr ‘Abdullah Tirmizī Mushkīn Qalam (for a record of his life, miracles and utterances see the untitled Sufi treatise appended to Persian MS 094, (ff. 145b- 188a). He is alo the author of a well-known Sufi poem, the <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Majmu‘ah-yi Rāz</title> (A.H. 1030, A.D. 1621). We are told by the author that it took him three years to write Mandqib-i Murtazavi, and that he intends to write Vjaz-i Mustafavii, a similar account of the life of the prophet Muhammad (f. <locus from="291r" to="291r">291r</locus>):ان شاه الله العزیز بعد از اختتام, اعجاز مصطفی کتابی جداگانه در مناقب اصحاب مستطاب رضی الله عنهم اجمعین که مکنون خاطر است بمقتضای الهی در خبر (کذا) تحریر آورده بر صحیفه ظهور جلوه گر خواهد گردانید...ختم شد این نامه در قرب سه سال . However, Kashfī did not survive to accomplish his desire and the latter was to be completed by <persName type="supplied" key="person_f3027">Mīr ‘Abd Allāh bin Mīr Hāshim shāh Ni‘mat allāh al-Husainī</persName> (see Rieu, BM 154a). In Manāqib-i Murtazavī Kashfī makes extensive use of the works of other authors, and relates stories some of which can be traced in other cultures long before the time of Imam ‘Ali, like the story of the man who is the victim of a cyclic tortur for his sin by being devoured by a bird and spat out to regain his life (f. 288b). It is mainly in prose, illustrated with verses by the author and selections from the works of other poets. After the first chapter, and a relatively lengthy preface, the text is divided into twelve bāb</summary>
